social_posts.post_text:
100 reps of -
Burpees
Kb swings
Body rows 
Box jumps 
For breakfast !!

Would I recommend everyone to do these ?
No.
Would I recommend it to anyone at all? 
Yes, only if you are a seasoned athlete or have been practising progressive loading and high rep workouts, to be done once in a while only as long as you also focus on strength work and correctives to address your imbalances. 

Why do I say so ?
Because, as a fitness professional, I can respect the mental strength and positive behavioral change that an individual may acquire from performing 100 or more repetitions in a row but when there’s such a big volume most of us don’t think of form trying to finish the reps and that’s a road straight to getting injured and also develop imbalances which defeats one of the main purposes of working out - strengthen bones and muscles, and improve your ability to do everyday activities.

However, i always love the challenge thrown at me by @theboxkohtao and once in a while like to kill a wod like this with a structure that works for me.

Tips if you are doing a high volume wod like this:
1. Warm up well, spend good amount of time to do some dynamic stretching and regressions with body weight or light weight.
2. Distribute or divide the reps for example - I did 10-15 reps of each exs as one round (but you can reduce the reps)
3. Scale down the movements to a regressed version. Ex : If you can’t do push-ups with proper form yet do the kneeling push-ups. If box jumps are scary then go for squat jumps.
4. Go only as fast as you can control. As long as you maintain the ROM and a good form, avoid going faster to compensate the above. It’s ok if you take a lil longer. It’s not worth it to risk injuries. 
5. Always do it with a partner to watch your form and to take the break in between as you take turns. 

As long as you take care of yourself - 
Go bananas !!! 🍌🍌🍌

I love combining Mobility with strength, Kettle bell variations with rotational movements and add plyo work as super sets. 
❇️Since shoulder is a ball and socket joint,  the girdle and upper back tend to hold tension and, as a result, motion in the area becomes restricted. So the  halo is an excellent shoulder and upper back mobility exercise to help reduce or prevent this lack of mobility. With the small barbell load and a arm movement around the body, this was great for wrist, arm and grip strength as well. 
❇️Rotating clean and press (switching hands in between) I love this for its co ordination challenge and rotational strength. 
❇️Split stance SA swing to press thanks to @cliftonharski and his #kettlebell videos my brain and body said fuck off many times but the load variability makes you a lot more aware of your position in the stance and gives your joints to get comfy and stronger at positions that we normally avoid focusing on (internal rotation of the hip and knees).
❇️Squat jumps to lunge jumps, my fav combo to actively recover and to give CNS the challenge to switch in between. I felt the difference in strength and effort immediately when I switch from squat to lunges and which one needs more work. 

❇️ The feedback we get from each of these exs where there is a combo or mix of two or three variations is so helpful in order to structure some workouts as we progress and I enjoy including these atleast once a week. Of course these are a lil advanced movements so if you are still new to KB work start with simple work like swings and loading them in your other functional exs.

These workouts are not new to me and I have been doin power lifts and barbell complex from a few years but the only diff compared to what I was doing 4 years ago is the reduction of reps and the way I load, the accessory work I hve included to support these type of workouts.

So I would never say don’t try something new but always start with regressions. This also depends on how many other disciplines you practice on a regular basis, if you have had injuries or imbalances, gone through pregnancy or taken a break for various other reasons etc.
In my scenario, I don’t go for insane reps with heavy weights anymore and limit the reps till the form is in check. I use body weight exs as supersets with higher reps to simulate the same intensity. The days I do heavy weight work, there also a lot of mobility work and accessory work with isolation exs and correctives. These small changes once or twice a week can take us a long way and help us perform better and achieve better results. 
This was one such workout - 4 clusters followed by 40 plank run and my personal fav - 15 dead stop KB swings.
❇️ Special mention for the dead stop swings - they are a great way to regress the Kb swings and still feel the intensity of the movement, helps you to avoid potentially accumulating bad reps and gets you to focus on the breathing and hinging pattern a bit more.

What’s power without the explosive strength ? 
Mandatory once a week work for the fast twitch muscle fibers!! 

Power output is affected by the speed of movement. By performing movements faster you can increase power, but explosive strength may not necessarily be affected by movement speed.

Conversely, explosive strength is affected by the speed of contraction, regardless of movement speed or the type of contraction. 

These exercises must be assessed, understood and developed for anyone to reach their full potential. Increase in both speed of movement (effects power) and speed of contraction (affects explosive strength) would be beneficial for any athlete regardless of skill level, sport or weight of external load.

I have kept all these movements to lower reps and higher weight so I could focus on max speed at the given time!

Two topics I wana address in this post :

• Fasted workouts specifically the day after binging. 
• Making home workouts more efficient. 

I use fasted workouts in many situations but in this post I am only Gona talk about why I use it as a hack the day after I indulge in extra carbs more than I need and sugary yummies. 

What is it ?
Fasted workouts don’t mean intermittent fasting, you simply wake up and workout without any consuming any food (water and black coffee ok) or items that spike your blood sugar levels.

Why is it helpful? 
For more fat burn or to push out extra glycogen (carbohydrates) stored in your muscles. When you are in fasted state you body burns through the glycogen for energy. In the absence of food for a short time, we create more sub stations for increased fat burn. 

Is it for everyone/ can you do it everyday? 
I don’t recommend it if you are trying to gain muscle mass. Certainly not everyday because you gotto vary these practices and for some of you feeding appropriately before workouts might be beneficial to perform better which will get the results. So make sure you consult an expert or your trainers who’s well aware of these.

But defly a good practice once in a while for that extra fat burn and detox, just don’t abuse this routine. This doesn’t mean you can overeat and indulge everyday and do fasted workouts to fix it. Know your limits and your body’s moderation levels.

Efficient home workouts :
1. Combinations with 1-2 variations that works multiple joints.
2. Divide them into flexion and extension chain exercises to get the full benefits of it.
3. Stick to 4-5 exs to optimise and perform the best.
4. Store easy Equipments at home like dumbbells, kettlebells and bands. I won’t lie socks can be great for some exs.
5. Don’t hesitate to regress the movements, you don’t always have to do fancy exs. 
6. Aim at 30-40 mins of workouts, you can combine with cardio if you have a machine at like a stationary bike, treadmill or a rowing machine.

But here’s what’s more important about protein requirement for women- 

The standard health guidelines globally says that women need less protein than men through out the month !!

False !
Women actually need more protein during the Luteal phase when progesterone peaks right after ovulation because progesterone is catabolic in nature, it stimulates deposition of body fat but has catabolic effects on protein metabolism which simply means it’s preparing the lining of your uterus so it’s breaking more protein to build the endometrium. 
Which is why women tend have more food cravings with both carbs and protein during the luteal phase of their cycle. It also holds a lot fluids in the body causing bloating (which I will address another time). 
So if we double the protein portion more than the standard guidelines which is one palm size or 0.8 grams of protein per kilogram of body weight right after ovulation, you can see the difference in your cravings and energy, which in turn helps in avoiding unnecessary weight gain during periods from all the binging. This may take some time or couple of months to feel the difference. 

And when I say standard guidelines these from RDA from the food and nutrition board, national institute of health eyv organisations that conduct many research and publish it for the whole world to follow. It’s good to see that few people are talking about these nutritional requirements and how it’s different for women. 

I’m Gona share some images soon about the portion sizes and what it looks like from the RDA and NHI etc. stay tuned … share it with people who need to see it!

Many of you ask about how I workout through the entire menstrual cycle or whether working out during periods is ok.
There is no research sayin that you should completely sit idle during the bleed week unless your body goes through a drastic change with pain and discomfort. In such cases there are under lying issues which you need to seek medical attention for.
For the rest of us with a regular menstrual cycle it’s absolutely okay to workout during periods and I have highlighted some of the options which you could follow every week. 
A woman with a normal regular cycle will have different hormones dominating every week, there is a high hormone phase and a low hormone phase with ovulation in between. 
First and foremost I’d like to point out that regardless of which week you are on, any kind of weight training is absolutely safe, the only thing that changes is the intensity at which you lift. 
Of course it’s very important to be intuitive and listen to your body as well but at the same time know and understand when it’s right to push hard with weights and go for HIIT (specially when testosterone peaks) and when should u avoid inversions etc. 

This is key for a lot of female athletes who don’t have too much control over their schedules and have to push boundaries at all times. But treating the body with a bit of deload specially when it’s high hormone phase could save from ligamentous injuries! 

More than your training routine it’s your eating that has to change with the hormones that change every week and has an impact on our metabolism.

For anything more in detail, you can always train with me and learn more!

I hope this gives you confidence to pick what is best for you to continue working out to give your body the boost that it needs specially with weight training that is so essential for women !!

Small changes in to your usual exercises will make a huge difference in the intensity and efficiency.

Weighted butterfly - if you hve been doin this stretch, add resistance to not just open up the hips and elongating the spine which is a good way to release tension and increase flexibility in the kinetic chain but also to strengthen it.

Copenhagen instead of side plank for Deficit or against gravity work - another great way to strengthen hip muscles and lateral stability without adding any weights. 

Weighted dead bugs - push the lower back down and close any gap so you get a proper brace or core engagement through out the movement. 

Beast pose bird dog - knees off the floor in quadruped position is a game changer for any core exercise and you hve to do it to feel it. Make sure the knees are directly under the belly button. 

These small tips will help you to progress better in many different ways by connecting so many other missing links !

Go to combinations for hammies, glutes and quads!
Here’s a better reason to work on glutes apart from aesthetics, Along with grip strength and muscle mass, glute strength (lower body) is linked to longevity and has been suggested as a biomarker of health related quality of life according to research. 

So welcome resistance training into your life if you haven’t yet. Could be body weight, usage of bands or heavier equipments as you progress!

The pelvic stability gained through glute strengthening helps maintain the integrity of the lower body’s closed kinetic chain. This means that if you were to lose balance for any reason your hip joint can withstand the disproportionate impact and limit the acute force’s effect on the knee.
This also doesn’t mean you only have to focus on growing your booty, make sure you work your way down as well. 
Lower body has some of our largest muscles and will have the most significant impact on our metabolism which is also essential for healthy lifestyle. 

In addition, Spanish squats are one of my favs to work on generating strength in the lower extremities without “over loading” the anterior knee structures which is great if you have any tendinopathy. Make sure you work with a coach or a Physio in order to keep the form in check!

Most women are skeptical about working out with weights specially in India because they think :
1. We become like men or too muscular 
2. They don’t need it. 

Both of the above are myths. 
1. Our genetic makeup prevents us from becoming like men or developing large muscles like them..
2. Women in general need weight training for the above mentioned benefits and specially as we age several changes occur in muscle composition. There is a natural decline in muscle mass, known as sarcopenia, which can lead to a reduction in strength and muscle function. Additionally, hormonal changes, particularly a decrease in estrogen during menopause, can contribute to these muscle changes. Regular exercise, especially strength training, becomes essential to counteract these effects, helping to maintain muscle mass, strength, and overall functional capacity.

Hope this can help y’all to explore weight training even if it’s light … if you have been doing body weight exercises it’s time for you to explore teeny tiny weights and if you have been lifting tiny weight it’s time to explore big girl weights 💪🏽

An article I have been helping to write about why women should lift weights and how does it help women in menopause picked my curiosity to post this. 

Can women be jacked like men - no our hormonal profile doesn’t facilitate to look like men. However we can achieve a healthy muscle composition which is essential for all women specially in menopause as we deplete some of the sex hormones that help us in fat metabolism.
Why should women focus on reducing muscle to fat ratio and why it’s more than just weight loss ? Why should we lift weights ? 

Muscles play a role in hormonal health by influencing the secretion and sensitivity of certain hormones. Regular exercise, including strength training, can enhance insulin sensitivity, helping regulate blood sugar levels. Additionally, muscle activity stimulates the release of hormones like growth hormone, which is essential for tissue repair and overall health. Exercise with weight training  also contributes to the balance of hormones like cortisol and adrenaline, promoting a healthier stress response. Overall, maintaining muscle health through exercise positively impacts hormonal balance and contributes to better metabolic health.
